text: Dear indignant book readers: a good portion of the people who see this trailer will not have read the books. Having not read the books, they'll look around for something to compare it to. If it wasn't X-Men, it was going to be Harry Potter. It's human nature to look for a point of reference when faced with something new, but with elements that seem vaguely familiar.  Screaming at people to read the books is a waste of time because the vast majority of people who watch films based on movies don't bother with the source material.  Case and point: The Wizard of Oz. Every other person in America knows this movie or has seen it. Yet how many of them do you HONESTLY think have read the books the film was based on?   Who cares if people think a movie that didn't come out yet might be a "British X-Men?" When they see the movie for themselves, they'll know differently. Know need to go through the comment section screaming at everyone like a nitwit.

text: I really hope this film does well, this as a movie franchise would be such an amazing break from all the comic book and teen dystopian movies that are plaguing the box office. There's been so many book adaptions out recently and I'd hate to see another good book series go to waste (ex: the Percy Jackson series and The Mortal Instruments series are great teen fantasy novels with a large following that should have been successful, but their films didn't hold up well).  I had heard of this book and had seen it around, it was until I saw the first trailer that I got intrigued enough to go out and read it. Seeing this second trailer now having officially finished the book, I'm honestly very excited! Although I'm a little concerned with this new version of Emma (she doesn't seem very similar to her book character, especially with the whole change in powers) I'm sure there's a reason for the change. It still looks like a faithful adaption, and Tim Burton seems like the perfect director to handle this series.

text: Of course I'm a little sad that Emma/Olive's powers were switched around but quite honestly, they still managed to make her such a freaking badass that I AM A-OKAY WITH ALL OF THIS.   I remember the author once stating that what mattered to him more was the integrity of the story and the relationship between Emma and Jacob being portrayed correctly.  From what I can tell, the essence and most importantly the *heart* and *soul* of the original novel has remained intact.  I'm okay with powers being switched, with tweaks to the original novel I loved so much being made, with this little band of orphans somehow bringing an old submarine to life instead of sailing away on a tiny boat, because... wow.  It looks like it's going to be awesome anyway.   Stay positive, guys!  A movie adaptation doesn't have to be 100% accurate to be good.  c:

text: I just... can't really be excited for this? Like people are making X-men jokes, but the fact is they have a point, because here the peculiarities are being played as superpowers in a lot of ways; but in most cases in the books their abilities are just... there. Olive is lighter than air, but that's all she can do - she can't manipulate air or weaponise it. She just floats. Hugh just happens to have a swarm of bees living inside him, Milton (?) is perpetually invisible. But their peculiarities are limited, and are just that: peculiarities. Not superpowers that make them 'superhuman', which is the tone I get from the trailers. They're just kids, who can each do one quite limited strange thing. And with that missing, I don't think I'll enjoy the film very much.

Millard doesn't bleed and reveal what he looks like which he did in the book, Emma suddenly has a perculiarity of air, Abe calls every day in the 1943 time loop all of a sudden, the psychologist is a woman (pretty sure it was a man in the book, and he is never mentioned as the bus driver), in the movie they don't take Miss Avocet when they take Miss Peregrine, and then Miss Avocet gets her eyes ripped out, I might be wrong but I'm pretty sure they made Enoch older and Bronwyn younger, Horace can somehow show his dreams, apparently Jake's kind-of-best friend from the start of the book doesn't exist, in the movie the shipwreck can suddenly become a functioning boat (WTAF) and they go to Blackpool on it (double WTAF)... I mean the last ten minutes is practically unrecognisable, and all the changes has led to a few minor plot holes. Also, why can't Dr Golan see the hollows in the movie? And what are they going to do for the sequel, given that they changed so much!?!

text: This movie was so fantastically bad that I don't even know where to begin-- but the worst part is that I know it's exactly the amount of trite and cliche that would make most people think it's "brilliant." The entire plot felt like it was written by a high schooler's idea of "deep and profound," it's far too stupid to be worthwhile to adults and too creepy to be appropriate for kids. When I first saw the preview I could guess more or less at the gist of the plot,and ofc it turned out more or less like what I suspected-- because it's just so chock full of cliche after cliche. The only worthwhile thing about it is the creativity in the 'weird' factor, but other than that it's like every character in this story acts like a melodramatic teenager's juvenile perception of what those people must be like-- as opposed to a mildly credible depiction.   (For example, the father doesn't act like an actual father, but like a self-absorbed teenager's idea of what a father might be like, "so sure of himself without really understanding or knowing" etc). You don't even need to see the film,  you can tell from just the trailer that the characters with "deep and profound understanding" will be the teenage boy and the blond teenage girl, who will ofc "find delicate and beautiful love while no one else understands." Sad that loads of viewers will think that this really is a wonderful depiction of characters and a wonderful story.
